<chapter xml:id="_simple_stress_and_strain">
<title>Simple Stress and Strain</title>
<section xml:id="_theory">
<title>Theory</title>
<tip>
<simpara>This section covers idealized simple stress and strain. In more complex cases, some of these simplifications may not apply.</simpara>
</tip>
<section xml:id="_loading">
<title>Loading</title>
<simpara>Components of engineering structures or mechanisms experience various forces. For example, the cylindrical bar below is used in a lifting mechanism and so it is subjected to <emphasis role="strong">tension</emphasis> force along the axis.</simpara>
<simpara>A member of a mechanism may experience loading in one of the following ways.</simpara>
<simpara>(a) Static, dead, or non-fluctuating loads e.g. force due to gravity<?asciidoc-br?>
(b) Live loads e.g. train on the railway<?asciidoc-br?>
(c) Impact or shock loads e.g. hammering<?asciidoc-br?>
(d) Fatigue, fluctuating, or altering loads e.g. repeated loaded swivel, crack propagation</simpara>
</section>
<section xml:id="_direct_or_normal_stress">
<title>Direct or Normal Stress (<inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[\sigma]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[\sigma]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>)</title>
<simpara>This is when a uniform-structured member or a bar is subjected to <emphasis role="marked"><emphasis role="strong">uniform</emphasis> tension or compression</emphasis>.</simpara>
<tip>
<informalequation>
<alt><![CDATA[\sigma\ (\text{stress}) = \frac{F\ (\text{load})}{A\ (\text{area})}\ \frac{N}{m^2}]]></alt>
<mathphrase><![CDATA[\sigma\ (\text{stress}) = \frac{F\ (\text{load})}{A\ (\text{area})}\ \frac{N}{m^2}]]></mathphrase>
</informalequation>
</tip>
</section>
<section xml:id="_direct_or_normal_strain">
<title>Direct or Normal Strain (<inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[\epsilon]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[\epsilon]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>)</title>
<simpara>This is a dimensionless measure of a change in length of a member, after it has been subjected to tension or compression.</simpara>
<tip>
<informalequation>
<alt><![CDATA[\epsilon\ (\text{strain}) = \frac{\Delta L\ (\text{change in length})}{L\ (\text{original length})}\ \frac{\cancel{m}}{\cancel{m}}]]></alt>
<mathphrase><![CDATA[\epsilon\ (\text{strain}) = \frac{\Delta L\ (\text{change in length})}{L\ (\text{original length})}\ \frac{\cancel{m}}{\cancel{m}}]]></mathphrase>
</informalequation>
</tip>
<simpara>Strain may be expressed as a percentage, <inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[\epsilon = \frac{\Delta L}{L} \times 100 \%]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[\epsilon = \frac{\Delta L}{L} \times 100 \%]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>.
Tensile stress and strain are considered positive, while compressive ones are considered negative.</simpara>
</section>
<section xml:id="_elastic_materials_hookes_law">
<title>Elastic Materials (Hooke&#8217;s Law, <inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[F = ke]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[F = ke]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>)</title>
<simpara>A member is said to be elastic or obey Hooke&#8217;s law if it returns to its original length when the load is withdrawn. In this case, the stress is proportional to strain.</simpara>
<tip>
<informalequation>
<alt><![CDATA[\frac{\sigma}{\epsilon} = constant]]></alt>
<mathphrase><![CDATA[\frac{\sigma}{\epsilon} = constant]]></mathphrase>
</informalequation>
</tip>
<simpara>Common classification of materials:</simpara>
<simpara>Homogeneous material&#8201;&#8212;&#8201;uniform structure without any flaws or discontinuities e.g. steel<?asciidoc-br?>
Inhomogeneous material&#8201;&#8212;&#8201;the structure varies from point to point e.g. concrete, some cast iron<?asciidoc-br?>
Isotropic&#8201;&#8212;&#8201;uniform properties throughout in all directions<?asciidoc-br?>
Anisotropic&#8201;&#8212;&#8201;varying properties<?asciidoc-br?>
Othotropic&#8201;&#8212;&#8201;different properties in different planes e.g. wood, some composites</simpara>
<simpara>Here, we assume homogeneous materials with isotropic properties.</simpara>
</section>
<section xml:id="_modulus_of_elasticity_youngs_modulus">
<title>Modulus of Elasticity (Young&#8217;s Modulus, <inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[E]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[E]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>)</title>
<simpara>The constant derived above, within which Hooke&#8217;s law applies, is referred to as the <emphasis>modulus of elasticity</emphasis> or the <emphasis>Young&#8217;s modulus</emphasis>, <emphasis role="strong">E</emphasis>.</simpara>
<tip>
<informalequation>
<alt><![CDATA[\frac{\sigma}{\epsilon} = E]]></alt>
<mathphrase><![CDATA[\frac{\sigma}{\epsilon} = E]]></mathphrase>
</informalequation>
<informalequation>
<alt><![CDATA[E = \frac{F}{A}/ \frac{\Delta L}{L} = \frac{FL}{A \Delta L}]]></alt>
<mathphrase><![CDATA[E = \frac{F}{A}/ \frac{\Delta L}{L} = \frac{FL}{A \Delta L}]]></mathphrase>
</informalequation>
</tip>
<simpara>The modulus of elasticity is assumed to be the same, both in tension or in compression. Since its value is large for most engineering materials, <inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[~ \times 10^9 N/m^2]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[~ \times 10^9 N/m^2]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>, the strain will be small, <inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[~ 0.3\%]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[~ 0.3\%]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>. Usually, the deformations are typically small with respect to the original dimension.</simpara>
</section>
<section xml:id="_tensile_test">
<title>Tensile Test</title>
<simpara>The modulus of elasticity is determined by carrying out a standard test as shown in the figure below. In this test, a circular bar of a uniform cross-section is subjected to a gradually increasing tensile load until failure occurs. The <emphasis role="marked">change in the <emphasis role="strong">gauge length</emphasis></emphasis> is recorded as the loading operation continues.</simpara>
<figure xml:id="img-tensileTest">
<title>Tensile test.</title>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject>
<imagedata fileref="solid-mechanics-figs/tensileTest.png" contentwidth="100%" align="left"/>
</imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>tensileTest</phrase></textobject>
</mediaobject>
</figure>
<simpara><emphasis role="marked">Origin to point <emphasis role="strong">A</emphasis>:</emphasis> <emphasis>Hooke&#8217;s law</emphasis> is obeyed. Stress is proportional to strain.<?asciidoc-br?>
<emphasis role="marked">At point <emphasis role="strong">A</emphasis>:</emphasis> <emphasis>limit of proportionality</emphasis><?asciidoc-br?>
<emphasis role="marked">Between points <emphasis role="strong">A</emphasis> and <emphasis role="strong">B</emphasis>:</emphasis> the material may still be elastic but Hooke&#8217;s law is not obeyed.<?asciidoc-br?>
<emphasis role="marked">At point <emphasis role="strong">B</emphasis>:</emphasis> <emphasis>elastic limit</emphasis><?asciidoc-br?>
In most practical cases, points <emphasis role="strong">A</emphasis> and <emphasis role="strong">B</emphasis> are coincident.<?asciidoc-br?>
<emphasis role="marked">Beyond point <emphasis role="strong">B</emphasis>:</emphasis> <emphasis>plastic deformation</emphasis><?asciidoc-br?>
Strains are not totally recoverable and permanent deformations are recorded when load is removed.<?asciidoc-br?>
<emphasis role="marked">At point <emphasis role="strong">C</emphasis>:</emphasis> <emphasis>upper yield point</emphasis><?asciidoc-br?>
<emphasis role="marked">At point <emphasis role="strong">D</emphasis>:</emphasis> <emphasis>lower yield point</emphasis><?asciidoc-br?>
A rapid increase in strain occurs without a corresponding increase in stress.<?asciidoc-br?>
<emphasis role="marked">Between points <emphasis role="strong">E</emphasis> and <emphasis role="strong">F</emphasis>:</emphasis> <emphasis>necking</emphasis> occurs<?asciidoc-br?>
The stress reaches the maximum value, the <emphasis>ultimate tensile strength</emphasis>.<?asciidoc-br?>
<emphasis role="marked">At point <emphasis role="strong">F</emphasis>:</emphasis> the specimen breaks</simpara>
<itemizedlist>
<listitem>
<simpara>The <emphasis role="strong">ductility</emphasis> is the capacity of a material to allow large plastic deformations.</simpara>
</listitem>
<listitem>
<simpara>For some materials, say, non-ferrous and high-carbon steel, the difference between points C and D cannot be detected. In such cases, a <emphasis role="strong">proof stress</emphasis> is used to show the onset of plastic strain.</simpara>
</listitem>
</itemizedlist>
</section>
<section xml:id="_poissons_ratio">
<title>Poisson&#8217;s Ratio (<inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[v]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[v]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>)</title>
<simpara>When a bar is subjected to a tension load, it experiences an increase in length, <inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[\Delta L]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[\Delta L]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>, giving a longitudinal strain in the bar, <inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[\epsilon_{Long}]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[\epsilon_{Long}]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>.</simpara>
<informalequation>
<alt><![CDATA[\epsilon_{Long} = \frac{\Delta L}{L}]]></alt>
<mathphrase><![CDATA[\epsilon_{Long} = \frac{\Delta L}{L}]]></mathphrase>
</informalequation>
<simpara>The breath, <inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[b]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[b]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>, and the depth, <inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[d]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[d]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>, of the bar will also reduce, thereby altering the lateral dimensions of the bar. The lateral strain, <inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[\epsilon_{Lat}]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[\epsilon_{Lat}]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>, can be given by the following equation.</simpara>
<tip>
<informalequation>
<alt><![CDATA[\epsilon_{Lat} = - \frac{\Delta b}{b} = - \frac{\Delta d}{d}]]></alt>
<mathphrase><![CDATA[\epsilon_{Lat} = - \frac{\Delta b}{b} = - \frac{\Delta d}{d}]]></mathphrase>
</informalequation>
<informalequation>
<alt><![CDATA[v (\text{Poisson's ratio}) = \frac{\epsilon_{Lat}}{\epsilon_{Long}} = - \frac{\Delta d}{d} \times \frac{L}{\Delta L}]]></alt>
<mathphrase><![CDATA[v (\text{Poisson's ratio}) = \frac{\epsilon_{Lat}}{\epsilon_{Long}} = - \frac{\Delta d}{d} \times \frac{L}{\Delta L}]]></mathphrase>
</informalequation>
<informalequation>
<alt><![CDATA[\epsilon_{Long} = \frac{\sigma_{Long}}{E} = \frac{\sigma}{E}]]></alt>
<mathphrase><![CDATA[\epsilon_{Long} = \frac{\sigma_{Long}}{E} = \frac{\sigma}{E}]]></mathphrase>
</informalequation>
<informalequation>
<alt><![CDATA[\epsilon_{Lat} = v \times \frac{\sigma}{E}]]></alt>
<mathphrase><![CDATA[\epsilon_{Lat} = v \times \frac{\sigma}{E}]]></mathphrase>
</informalequation>
</tip>
</section>
<section xml:id="_modulus_of_rigidity">
<title>Modulus of Rigidity (<inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[G]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[G]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>)</title>
<section xml:id="_shear_stress">
<title>Shear Stress (<inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[\tau]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[\tau]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>)</title>
<tip>
<informalequation>
<alt><![CDATA[\tau (\text{shear stress}) = \frac{F (\text{shear load})}{A (\text{area resisting shear})}]]></alt>
<mathphrase><![CDATA[\tau (\text{shear stress}) = \frac{F (\text{shear load})}{A (\text{area resisting shear})}]]></mathphrase>
</informalequation>
<informalequation>
<alt><![CDATA[\tau (\text{in double shear stress}) = \frac{F}{2 \times A }]]></alt>
<mathphrase><![CDATA[\tau (\text{in double shear stress}) = \frac{F}{2 \times A }]]></mathphrase>
</informalequation>
</tip>
</section>
<section xml:id="_shear_strain">
<title>Shear Strain (<inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[\gamma]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[\gamma]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>)</title>
<informalequation>
<alt><![CDATA[\gamma = \frac{\Delta L}{L}]]></alt>
<mathphrase><![CDATA[\gamma = \frac{\Delta L}{L}]]></mathphrase>
</informalequation>
<itemizedlist>
<listitem>
<simpara>The <emphasis role="strong">modulus of rigidity</emphasis>, <inlineequation><alt><![CDATA[G]]></alt><mathphrase><![CDATA[G]]></mathphrase></inlineequation>, or <emphasis role="strong">shear modulus</emphasis> is comparable to modulus of elasticity and it is calculated as follows.</simpara>
</listitem>
</itemizedlist>
<tip>
<informalequation>
<alt><![CDATA[G = \frac{\tau}{\gamma} = \text{constant}]]></alt>
<mathphrase><![CDATA[G = \frac{\tau}{\gamma} = \text{constant}]]></mathphrase>
</informalequation>
</tip>
</section>
